00:01:04.540 --> 00:01:06.990
PROFESSOR: Well, today, we have
a chance to put away the

00:01:06.990 --> 00:01:08.970
equations and have some fun.

00:01:08.970 --> 00:01:12.370
With me is Professor Sandy Hill
from the University of

00:01:12.370 --> 00:01:13.970
Massachusetts at Amherst.

00:01:13.970 --> 00:01:17.870
And Sandy, maybe you could just
give us a quick tour of

00:01:17.870 --> 00:01:18.860
what we have here.

00:01:18.860 --> 00:01:19.590
SANDY HILL: OK.

00:01:19.590 --> 00:01:22.070
We'll be dealing with about
four instruments today.

00:01:22.070 --> 00:01:24.800
Two of them generate signals,
and two of them display and

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:26.400
analyze signals.

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:30.180
The first, and perhaps simplest,
is simply an RC

00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:34.440
audio generator, that will put
out a variety wave shapes.

00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:36.510
And we'll look at that
in a moment.

00:01:36.510 --> 00:01:39.340
Over to the right is a device
that will allow us to study

00:01:39.340 --> 00:01:42.590
amplitude modulation and the
various flavors of it.

00:01:42.590 --> 00:01:44.950
Down below is a standard
oscilloscope to look at the

00:01:44.950 --> 00:01:47.850
signals in the time domain so
we can see their shape.

00:01:47.850 --> 00:01:50.790
And then, finally the spectrum
analyzer will analyze the

00:01:50.790 --> 00:01:52.750
signal into its Fourier
components.

00:01:52.750 --> 00:01:55.250
And we'll display those, so you
get to see the spectral

00:01:55.250 --> 00:01:57.650
content of a signal.

00:01:57.650 --> 00:02:00.490
PROFESSOR: Now, we'll be seeing
all of these in a fair

00:02:00.490 --> 00:02:04.760
amount of detail as we go
through the demonstrations.

00:02:04.760 --> 00:02:07.770
But maybe we can begin just
with the signal generator.

00:02:07.770 --> 00:02:11.030
SANDY HILL: OK, let's
look quickly at the

00:02:11.030 --> 00:02:12.390
various buttons involved.

00:02:12.390 --> 00:02:14.730
There's a lot of flexibility
with this device.

00:02:14.730 --> 00:02:18.590
The top three buttons here allow
us to change from one

00:02:18.590 --> 00:02:21.530
simple wave form to another one,
a sine wave, a triangle

00:02:21.530 --> 00:02:23.330
wave, a square wave.

00:02:23.330 --> 00:02:26.490
And right below it is a button
that will allow us to change

00:02:26.490 --> 00:02:28.390
the size of the signal.

00:02:28.390 --> 00:02:32.290
Moving over towards the left,
we can change the DC offset

00:02:32.290 --> 00:02:36.790
which varies the signal,
the level upon

00:02:36.790 --> 00:02:38.550
which the signal rides.

00:02:38.550 --> 00:02:40.390
PROFESSOR: And we'll be using
that actually when we

00:02:40.390 --> 00:02:42.090
demonstrate amplitude
modulation.

00:02:42.090 --> 00:02:44.540
SANDY HILL: That's right And
then finally, there's a way of

00:02:44.540 --> 00:02:47.350
changing the frequency of the
signal, either changing it by

00:02:47.350 --> 00:02:50.770
a factor of 10 or a vernier
adjustment, if you want very

00:02:50.770 --> 00:02:53.850
specific adjustments, very
delicate changes.

00:02:53.850 --> 00:02:54.190
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:02:54.190 --> 00:02:58.090
So maybe we can just vary some
of this and see what a little

00:02:58.090 --> 00:02:59.040
bit of it looks like.

00:02:59.040 --> 00:02:59.870
SANDY HILL: All right.

00:02:59.870 --> 00:03:04.130
What we have displayed at this
point is the effect of pushing

00:03:04.130 --> 00:03:05.300
the sine wave button.

00:03:05.300 --> 00:03:09.060
And so displayed down here
is a 500 Hertz sine wave.

00:03:09.060 --> 00:03:10.240
In fact, let's listen to that.

00:03:10.240 --> 00:03:11.490
PROFESSOR: Great.

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:16.790
SANDY HILL: And the scope is
said to have one millisecond

00:03:16.790 --> 00:03:19.260
for each division here.

00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:21.900
By varying the amplitude
knob can make the sine

00:03:21.900 --> 00:03:23.410
wave smaller or larger.

00:03:23.410 --> 00:03:26.010
The ear isn't too sensitive
to that.

00:03:26.010 --> 00:03:28.400
By changing the DC offset,
it simply rides

00:03:28.400 --> 00:03:29.515
on a different level.

00:03:29.515 --> 00:03:32.260
It's like putting a
battery in series.

00:03:32.260 --> 00:03:36.360
And changing the frequency,
you get a very perceptible

00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:38.230
change, a lower frequency.

00:03:38.230 --> 00:03:40.570
It takes longer to sweep
through a period.

00:03:40.570 --> 00:03:44.256
Higher frequency, it takes
a shorter amount of time.

00:03:44.256 --> 00:03:48.060
And also, we can change the wave
shape itself from a sine

00:03:48.060 --> 00:03:51.890
wave to a triangle wave--

00:03:51.890 --> 00:03:54.840
and you notice that has
a richer sound to it--

00:03:54.840 --> 00:03:58.210
and then finally to a square
wave, which is an even

00:03:58.210 --> 00:04:00.510
brighter sound.

00:04:00.510 --> 00:04:04.640
PROFESSOR: And actually, as you
realize from the previous

00:04:04.640 --> 00:04:07.980
lectures, with the triangle and
square wave with the same

00:04:07.980 --> 00:04:11.740
fundamental as the sine wave,
the richness comes in because

00:04:11.740 --> 00:04:17.880
of the higher harmonics in the
Fourier series representation.

00:04:17.880 --> 00:04:20.790
OK, well let's go back
to the sine wave.

00:04:20.790 --> 00:04:23.770
And we'll use that to take
a closer look at

00:04:23.770 --> 00:04:25.190
the spectrum analyzer.

00:04:25.190 --> 00:04:25.720
SANDY HILL: OK.

00:04:25.720 --> 00:04:28.140
PROFESSOR: We'll look at a block
diagram of the spectrum

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:32.190
analyzer shortly, but first
let's just look at a few quick

00:04:32.190 --> 00:04:34.360
things to get a feel for it.

00:04:34.360 --> 00:04:36.970
We have, of course,
the time domain

00:04:36.970 --> 00:04:39.890
display of the sine wave.

00:04:39.890 --> 00:04:44.230
And the spectrum analyzer gives
us a frequency domain

00:04:44.230 --> 00:04:46.450
analysis and display.

00:04:46.450 --> 00:04:52.540
And the vertical axis
is the amplitude.

00:04:52.540 --> 00:04:55.070
The horizontal axis
is frequency.

00:04:55.070 --> 00:05:00.150
And as it's set currently, the
frequency axis goes from DC--

00:05:00.150 --> 00:05:01.150
zero--

00:05:01.150 --> 00:05:02.480
up to 2 kilohertz.

00:05:02.480 --> 00:05:04.620
And that, of course,
can be varied on

00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:06.950
the spectrum analyzer.

00:05:06.950 --> 00:05:10.120
And since we have a sine wave
input, we get, as we would

00:05:10.120 --> 00:05:13.820
expect, a line spectrum,
corresponding to the frequency

00:05:13.820 --> 00:05:15.160
of the sine wave.

00:05:15.160 --> 00:05:18.970
Now, in fact, we can measure
that frequency because the

00:05:18.970 --> 00:05:23.840
spectrum analyzer has a cursor
associated with it, which I've

00:05:23.840 --> 00:05:25.600
just enabled.

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:28.900
And this line is the
cursor line.

00:05:28.900 --> 00:05:32.480
There is a read out for the
frequency and a read out for

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:34.500
the amplitude.

00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:37.390
And let's position
the cursor on the

00:05:37.390 --> 00:05:40.320
frequency of the sine wave.

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:44.520
And we're getting close.

00:05:44.520 --> 00:05:49.530
And there we are at the
frequency of the sine wave.

00:05:49.530 --> 00:05:53.350
And we can read out, in fact,
that it's 500 cycles.

00:05:53.350 --> 00:05:55.260
And this is the amplitude.

00:05:55.260 --> 00:05:58.910
And, of course, you could verify
the frequency also in

00:05:58.910 --> 00:06:01.900
the time domain display,
simply by measuring the

00:06:01.900 --> 00:06:05.690
frequency or the period.

00:06:05.690 --> 00:06:08.310
SANDY HILL: This is set at
still one millisecond per

00:06:08.310 --> 00:06:08.940
centimeter.

00:06:08.940 --> 00:06:10.330
So that is 500 Hertz.

00:06:10.330 --> 00:06:11.640
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:16.330
Well now maybe what we can
do is vary the frequency.

00:06:16.330 --> 00:06:18.950
Let's vary the frequency of
the sine wave generator.

00:06:18.950 --> 00:06:20.030
Maybe also listen to it?

00:06:20.030 --> 00:06:21.110
SANDY HILL: I'll turn
on the tone.

00:06:21.110 --> 00:06:23.130
Yep.

00:06:23.130 --> 00:06:25.550
OK, I'll make the frequency
higher.

00:06:25.550 --> 00:06:26.330
And you'll see a

00:06:26.330 --> 00:06:28.810
correspondence in the time domain.

00:06:28.810 --> 00:06:33.040
The frequency clearly goes up,
and that line of the spectrum

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:35.560
also migrates up away
from the cursor.

00:06:35.560 --> 00:06:37.690
PROFESSOR: OK, and let me just
point out again that this is

00:06:37.690 --> 00:06:38.610
the cursor line.

00:06:38.610 --> 00:06:40.680
This isn't the spectra line.

00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:46.560
And this is the frequency
content of the sine wave.

00:06:46.560 --> 00:06:49.230
SANDY HILL: We can also change
the amplitude of that line by

00:06:49.230 --> 00:06:53.240
making the sine wave
itself smaller.

00:06:53.240 --> 00:06:55.880
And you notice the intensity
of it goes--

00:06:55.880 --> 00:06:57.420
PROFESSOR: While you do that,
let me just position the

00:06:57.420 --> 00:07:01.790
cursor if I can on
the sine wave.

00:07:01.790 --> 00:07:04.880
And now as you vary the
amplitude, we should, in fact,

00:07:04.880 --> 00:07:08.685
see this vary.

00:07:08.685 --> 00:07:10.641
SANDY HILL: Well,
that's right.

00:07:10.641 --> 00:07:11.130
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:07:11.130 --> 00:07:15.460
Now as Sandy varied the
frequency, he did it slowly

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:19.590
and we saw the line move
as a single line.

00:07:19.590 --> 00:07:21.500
Maybe now, Sandy, you
could vary the

00:07:21.500 --> 00:07:22.970
frequency more rapidly.

00:07:22.970 --> 00:07:29.583
And what will happen is that, in
fact, what we'll get if I--

00:07:29.583 --> 00:07:31.865
SANDY HILL: There'll be
a spreading as we go--

00:07:31.865 --> 00:07:33.430
PROFESSOR: Let me turn
the cursor off.

00:07:33.430 --> 00:07:37.870
And what we'll see is a
spreading of the line, so that

00:07:37.870 --> 00:07:39.840
the frequency content
is richer.

00:07:39.840 --> 00:07:42.770
And, in fact, the analysis of
this is considerably more

00:07:42.770 --> 00:07:43.560
complicated.

00:07:43.560 --> 00:07:48.050
It corresponds to frequency
modulation, where Sandy is now

00:07:48.050 --> 00:07:49.175
the modulating signal.

00:07:49.175 --> 00:07:49.910
SANDY HILL: That's right.

00:07:49.910 --> 00:07:53.890
PROFESSOR: And we won't really
be going into issues of

00:07:53.890 --> 00:07:57.870
frequency modulation in any
more detail in this

00:07:57.870 --> 00:07:58.710
demonstration.

00:07:58.710 --> 00:08:00.670
SANDY HILL: Right.

00:08:00.670 --> 00:08:03.240
PROFESSOR: OK, well now let's
go to the overhead projector

00:08:03.240 --> 00:08:05.460
and take a look at a
block diagram of

00:08:05.460 --> 00:08:06.710
the spectrum analyzer.

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:14.040
The specific spectrum analyzer
that we're using in the

00:08:14.040 --> 00:08:18.420
demonstration is made by
Rockland Systems, referred to

00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:22.320
as the Rockland Systems
Model FFT 512.

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:29.980
And basically, the idea is to
sample the incoming wave form,

00:08:29.980 --> 00:08:33.919
convert that into digital form,
and then the spectrum,

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:38.929
in fact, is computed digitally
using a microprocessor.

00:08:38.929 --> 00:08:45.330
So the overall system block
diagram first consists of a

00:08:45.330 --> 00:08:48.280
system which is a
low pass filter.

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:54.100
And this low pass filter is
used in advance of the

00:08:54.100 --> 00:08:59.580
sampling process to basically
reduce the artifacts that are

00:08:59.580 --> 00:09:01.470
introduced due to sampling.

00:09:01.470 --> 00:09:05.490
And although we haven't talked
yet about sampling and the

00:09:05.490 --> 00:09:09.200
associated artifacts, basically,
as we'll see in the

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:14.480
upcoming lectures, in order to
sample a wave form and convert

00:09:14.480 --> 00:09:17.870
it into digital form, it
requires that the wave form

00:09:17.870 --> 00:09:19.990
first be low pass filtered.

00:09:19.990 --> 00:09:24.440
So this low pass filter is
referred to-- and will be in

00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:25.280
later lectures--

00:09:25.280 --> 00:09:27.800
as an anti-aliasing filter.

00:09:27.800 --> 00:09:32.840
And this low pass filtered wave
form is then converted to

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:34.750
a sequence.

00:09:34.750 --> 00:09:39.730
And so a sequence is generated
for which the sequence values

00:09:39.730 --> 00:09:46.590
are simply samples of the
low pass filtered input.

00:09:46.590 --> 00:09:50.620
This low pass filtered
input is then put

00:09:50.620 --> 00:09:52.340
into digital memory.

00:09:52.340 --> 00:09:56.730
Basically, a time block of it
is put into digital memory,

00:09:56.730 --> 00:09:59.620
and so that's what we
have down here.

00:09:59.620 --> 00:10:02.340
Here is the sequence.

00:10:02.340 --> 00:10:06.520
The sequence is put into
digital memory.

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:11.470
And then an arithmetic processor
computes for the

00:10:11.470 --> 00:10:13.770
samples in this memory.

00:10:13.770 --> 00:10:18.430
It computes the Fourier
transform or the spectrum.

00:10:18.430 --> 00:10:22.810
And after the spectrum is
computed and put either into

00:10:22.810 --> 00:10:26.860
the same or a different memory,
that is then put

00:10:26.860 --> 00:10:31.560
through a conversion process
back to a continuous time

00:10:31.560 --> 00:10:37.210
signal, and finally, put out on
the display that we've been

00:10:37.210 --> 00:10:39.000
seeing in the demonstration.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:43.190
And so this is just indicative
of the display.

00:10:43.190 --> 00:10:46.900
So basically, the idea then
is that the input

00:10:46.900 --> 00:10:49.410
wave form comes in.

00:10:49.410 --> 00:10:53.950
It's filtered and sampled and
captured on a block basis, put

00:10:53.950 --> 00:10:58.480
into a digital memory, and then,
a digital computer or

00:10:58.480 --> 00:11:02.250
microprocessor computes
the Fourier transform.

00:11:02.250 --> 00:11:05.530
And then that Fourier transform
is what we see on

00:11:05.530 --> 00:11:06.930
the display.

00:11:06.930 --> 00:11:10.840
So what we're computing, of
course, are samples of the

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:12.830
Fourier transform.

00:11:12.830 --> 00:11:16.040
And so, for example, if the
input-- let's say--

00:11:16.040 --> 00:11:20.680
was a rectangular pulse whose
Fourier transform is of the

00:11:20.680 --> 00:11:24.030
form of a sine(x) over x
function, what we would, in

00:11:24.030 --> 00:11:28.700
fact, see on the display are
samples of that at discrete

00:11:28.700 --> 00:11:29.900
frequencies.

00:11:29.900 --> 00:11:36.140
Or if as we have an input which
is a square wave, what

00:11:36.140 --> 00:11:40.560
will generate through the
spectrum analyzer are the

00:11:40.560 --> 00:11:45.760
Fourier series coefficients or
equivalently, the harmonics

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:48.720
associated with the
square wave.

00:11:48.720 --> 00:11:53.950
OK, well, let's now go back to
the equipment and look at the

00:11:53.950 --> 00:11:55.200
spectrum analyzer.

00:11:57.700 --> 00:12:01.640
We'll look at the square wave
through the spectrum analyzer

00:12:01.640 --> 00:12:06.040
shortly, but first what we have
is what we saw before,

00:12:06.040 --> 00:12:07.920
which is the sine wave.

00:12:07.920 --> 00:12:12.450
And just to point out, again,
the fact that the sine wave

00:12:12.450 --> 00:12:16.550
spectrum, of course, is just a
single line corresponding to

00:12:16.550 --> 00:12:19.080
the fundamental frequency.

00:12:19.080 --> 00:12:24.070
And here we have a frequency
scale now that goes from 0 to

00:12:24.070 --> 00:12:25.640
5 kilohertz.

00:12:25.640 --> 00:12:29.680
And this is then the 500
cycle sine wave.

00:12:29.680 --> 00:12:35.240
And, in fact, we can flip the
cursor on and I happen to just

00:12:35.240 --> 00:12:37.110
magically have it positioned
correctly.

00:12:37.110 --> 00:12:41.530
And we see that it's a
500 cycle sine wave.

00:12:41.530 --> 00:12:43.030
SANDY HILL: Might be
interesting, Al, to go and

00:12:43.030 --> 00:12:45.770
look at a richer set of signals,
such as the triangle

00:12:45.770 --> 00:12:48.730
wave and the square wave--
things that are conveniently

00:12:48.730 --> 00:12:50.650
on the signal generator
itself.

00:12:50.650 --> 00:12:54.000
I'll switch over to
a square wave now.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:57.340
And what you see is
all the harmonics

00:12:57.340 --> 00:13:00.064
coming up, being displayed.

00:13:00.064 --> 00:13:02.460
PROFESSOR: OK, it's actually
interesting to point out, I

00:13:02.460 --> 00:13:07.460
think, that the square wave,
as we know, is an

00:13:07.460 --> 00:13:08.940
odd harmonic function.

00:13:08.940 --> 00:13:14.470
And so, in fact, the even
harmonics are missing in the

00:13:14.470 --> 00:13:15.220
square wave.

00:13:15.220 --> 00:13:17.030
So this is the fundamental.

00:13:17.030 --> 00:13:20.320
This is the third harmonic,
fifth harmonic, et cetera.

00:13:20.320 --> 00:13:24.940
And then the amplitude of
the square wave decays

00:13:24.940 --> 00:13:27.870
proportional to 1 over f, which
is the kind of analysis

00:13:27.870 --> 00:13:30.000
that we've gone through in
looking at Fourier series.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:33.150
SANDY HILL: Right, and if we
switch to the triangle wave,

00:13:33.150 --> 00:13:36.730
instead of their decaying as 1
over f, the harmonics decay as

00:13:36.730 --> 00:13:37.800
1 over f squared.

00:13:37.800 --> 00:13:39.980
And you see they drop off
much more quickly.

00:13:39.980 --> 00:13:41.310
PROFESSOR: And again,
of course, it's an

00:13:41.310 --> 00:13:43.020
odd harmonic signal.

00:13:43.020 --> 00:13:47.730
And so the even numbered
harmonics are missing.

00:13:47.730 --> 00:13:52.450
And maybe just to kind of
emphasize the point, we can

00:13:52.450 --> 00:13:55.720
show the sine wave again and
the square wave again.

00:13:55.720 --> 00:13:59.360
SANDY HILL: We'll go through
from the most bland to the

00:13:59.360 --> 00:14:01.510
richer to the richest.

00:14:01.510 --> 00:14:02.750
PROFESSOR: OK, and it's
really kind of

00:14:02.750 --> 00:14:03.750
interesting and dramatic--

00:14:03.750 --> 00:14:04.650
SANDY HILL: It's
fun to do that.

00:14:04.650 --> 00:14:06.130
PROFESSOR: --to see the
harmonics pop in.

00:14:06.130 --> 00:14:07.900
SANDY HILL: While we're at the
square wave, let me fiddle

00:14:07.900 --> 00:14:10.100
with the frequency of the square
wave, and we can see

00:14:10.100 --> 00:14:13.970
the duality of the time
and frequency domains.

00:14:13.970 --> 00:14:16.480
That is, as you compress things
in the time domain,

00:14:16.480 --> 00:14:19.920
such as this, going to a higher
frequency square wave,

00:14:19.920 --> 00:14:22.620
the harmonics wonder further
away from each other.

00:14:22.620 --> 00:14:25.950
SANDY HILL: So this is
the fundamental.

00:14:25.950 --> 00:14:28.810
The second harmonic
is missing.

00:14:28.810 --> 00:14:30.290
This is the third harmonic.

00:14:30.290 --> 00:14:31.730
