00:20:02.040 --> 00:20:08.780
And now what we'd like to focus
on is the modulator and

00:20:08.780 --> 00:20:12.215
talk a little bit about
modulation and demodulation

00:20:12.215 --> 00:20:13.800
and demonstrate it.

00:20:13.800 --> 00:20:18.510
And let's begin that by first
taking a look at a block

00:20:18.510 --> 00:20:20.940
diagram of the modulator
system.

00:20:24.170 --> 00:20:27.260
Well, as we've discussed in a
previous lecture, amplitude

00:20:27.260 --> 00:20:32.790
modulation basically consists of
multiplying the modulating

00:20:32.790 --> 00:20:36.900
signal by an appropriate
carrier, illustrated here, as

00:20:36.900 --> 00:20:41.870
we've seen previously, for the
case of a sinusoidal carrier.

00:20:41.870 --> 00:20:45.930
And then, specifically for
sinusoidal amplitude

00:20:45.930 --> 00:20:51.580
modulation, we may or may not
inject some carrier signal--

00:20:51.580 --> 00:20:53.660
A times the carrier.

00:20:53.660 --> 00:20:59.610
Or equivalently, if we look at
the modulated output, the

00:20:59.610 --> 00:21:03.800
injection of the carrier is
equivalent, mathematically, to

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:07.310
simply adding a DC offset
or a constant to

00:21:07.310 --> 00:21:09.250
the modulating signal.

00:21:09.250 --> 00:21:14.490
And, as you recall when we
talked about this, the idea of

00:21:14.490 --> 00:21:19.310
injecting a carrier or not is
related to the issue of

00:21:19.310 --> 00:21:22.860
whether or not we want to do
synchronous or asynchronous

00:21:22.860 --> 00:21:24.290
demodulation.

00:21:24.290 --> 00:21:27.540
The asynchronous demodulation
corresponding to the simple

00:21:27.540 --> 00:21:30.050
use of an envelope detector.

00:21:30.050 --> 00:21:34.250
And to remind you of the wave
forms that are involved,

00:21:34.250 --> 00:21:38.230
again, I show two that
we saw previously.

00:21:38.230 --> 00:21:44.360
And for the case, this is for
one value of the amount of

00:21:44.360 --> 00:21:45.720
carrier that's injected.

00:21:45.720 --> 00:21:50.170
And this is for an amount of
carrier injected that's less.

00:21:50.170 --> 00:21:54.560
And this, in fact, corresponds
to what we refer to as 50%

00:21:54.560 --> 00:22:00.020
modulation, and this is the
case of 100% modulation.

00:22:00.020 --> 00:22:04.810
Well, the modulating system
that we're using in this

00:22:04.810 --> 00:22:08.630
demonstration is basically
of the form that

00:22:08.630 --> 00:22:10.160
we're indicating here.

00:22:10.160 --> 00:22:16.020
And a simple block diagram for
it is more or less identical

00:22:16.020 --> 00:22:17.820
to what we just saw.

00:22:17.820 --> 00:22:22.400
Specifically, the modulating
signal is

00:22:22.400 --> 00:22:25.010
multiplied by the carrier.

00:22:25.010 --> 00:22:29.300
And there also is the capability
of injecting some

00:22:29.300 --> 00:22:33.420
additional carrier, meaning
adding it to the output of

00:22:33.420 --> 00:22:34.430
this product.

00:22:34.430 --> 00:22:38.900
And so the modulated output can
have a variable percent

00:22:38.900 --> 00:22:39.770
modulation--

00:22:39.770 --> 00:22:44.000
the percent modulation being
changed, depending on how we

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:46.690
set this variable gain.

00:22:46.690 --> 00:22:50.450
Now, in addition to sinusoidal
modulation--

00:22:50.450 --> 00:22:53.980
in fact, for the particular
system that we're using, we

00:22:53.980 --> 00:22:56.350
have somewhat more
flexibility.

00:22:56.350 --> 00:22:59.340
We can use, in addition to a
sinusoidal carrier at this

00:22:59.340 --> 00:23:04.640
point, we can alternatively
choose a square wave carrier

00:23:04.640 --> 00:23:07.540
or a triangular carrier.

00:23:07.540 --> 00:23:10.600
And, as we'll indicate in a
moment when we illustrate

00:23:10.600 --> 00:23:14.280
this, there are some specific
advantages to using, for

00:23:14.280 --> 00:23:17.300
example, a square
wave carrier.

00:23:17.300 --> 00:23:21.890
So this is a somewhat simplified
version of--

00:23:21.890 --> 00:23:26.730
or rather block diagram of the
modulating system that we're

00:23:26.730 --> 00:23:27.950
demonstrating.

00:23:27.950 --> 00:23:32.010
The external modulating input
here, a choice of carrier with

00:23:32.010 --> 00:23:35.100
also the capability for
injecting some additional

00:23:35.100 --> 00:23:37.350
carrier into the output.

00:23:37.350 --> 00:23:39.490
OK, now let's go back
to the equipment and

00:23:39.490 --> 00:23:42.100
take a look at this.

00:23:42.100 --> 00:23:45.290
Well, Sandy, maybe to begin,
you can just point out what

00:23:45.290 --> 00:23:47.800
some of the controls are
on the modulator box.

00:23:47.800 --> 00:23:50.180
SANDY HILL: OK, there
are some interesting

00:23:50.180 --> 00:23:52.230
points to look at here.

00:23:52.230 --> 00:23:54.860
This is an input for
an external signal.

00:23:54.860 --> 00:23:57.330
We'll be taking a signal right
out of the signal generator

00:23:57.330 --> 00:23:58.670
and putting it in here.

00:23:58.670 --> 00:24:01.960
And that will be the signal
that will be modulated,

00:24:01.960 --> 00:24:03.560
according to the carrier.

00:24:03.560 --> 00:24:06.450
The carrier is generated
internally in this device.

00:24:06.450 --> 00:24:08.870
And there are several ways
of controlling it.

00:24:08.870 --> 00:24:12.170
One is the amount of
carrier injection.

00:24:12.170 --> 00:24:16.410
One is the wave form of the
carrier itself-- and this is

00:24:16.410 --> 00:24:19.530
typically sinusoidal in the
broadcast industry, but others

00:24:19.530 --> 00:24:21.710
are interesting to
look at as well.

00:24:21.710 --> 00:24:24.110
The output that will be
displaying on both the

00:24:24.110 --> 00:24:27.310
spectrum analyzer and scope
comes out here.

00:24:27.310 --> 00:24:30.580
And then farther over to the
left, there are some knobs for

00:24:30.580 --> 00:24:33.440
changing the frequency of
the carrier signal.

00:24:33.440 --> 00:24:37.340
PROFESSOR: OK, let me also
just point out again for

00:24:37.340 --> 00:24:40.780
emphasis that changing the
carrier level, as we've talked

00:24:40.780 --> 00:24:43.800
about, is mathematically
equivalent to changing the DC

00:24:43.800 --> 00:24:45.990
level of the modulating
signal.

00:24:45.990 --> 00:24:49.545
And that's also what affects the
percent modulation as we

00:24:49.545 --> 00:24:51.320
had just discussed.

00:24:51.320 --> 00:24:56.930
Now what we have set up is a
sinusoidal modulating signal

00:24:56.930 --> 00:24:59.050
and a sinusoidal
little carrier.

00:24:59.050 --> 00:25:04.120
And, as usual, we have the time
wave form displayed here.

00:25:04.120 --> 00:25:06.840
And so this is the
modulated signal.

00:25:06.840 --> 00:25:10.070
And then on the spectrum
analyzer, we have

00:25:10.070 --> 00:25:11.870
the spectral display.

00:25:11.870 --> 00:25:14.750
And this is the carrier
signal.

00:25:14.750 --> 00:25:16.620
That's the carrier frequency.

00:25:16.620 --> 00:25:21.070
And these side bands then
correspond to the side bands

00:25:21.070 --> 00:25:23.270
associated with the
modulating signal.

00:25:23.270 --> 00:25:27.730
So this is the spectrum of the
total modulated output, right?

00:25:27.730 --> 00:25:28.480
SANDY HILL: Right.

00:25:28.480 --> 00:25:30.990
It's interesting to vary some
of these parameters.

00:25:30.990 --> 00:25:33.560
You can see the sinusoidal
modulating

00:25:33.560 --> 00:25:34.970
shape at this point.

00:25:34.970 --> 00:25:39.010
Let me switch that to
a triangular shape.

00:25:39.010 --> 00:25:42.500
And, again, it's a little hard
to sink in both the modulating

00:25:42.500 --> 00:25:45.150
signal and the carrier, so you
see the carrier kind of

00:25:45.150 --> 00:25:47.630
wondering by, but there it is.

00:25:47.630 --> 00:25:49.950
Another thing that can be varied
is the amplitude of the

00:25:49.950 --> 00:25:50.950
modulating signal.

00:25:50.950 --> 00:25:52.280
I'll make it smaller--

00:25:52.280 --> 00:25:54.960
you'll see the side
bands go away--

00:25:54.960 --> 00:25:58.070
until finally we have a pure
sinusoidal carrier--

00:25:58.070 --> 00:26:00.040
as I bring them back in.

00:26:00.040 --> 00:26:01.440
Again, this is triangular.

00:26:01.440 --> 00:26:04.160
There would be harmonics there
that maybe they're a little

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:06.560
hard to see in the spectrum
analyzer.

00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:10.570
I'll go back first to a square
wave modulating signal, which

00:26:10.570 --> 00:26:14.630
is, again, you can see the
square wave on top and one on

00:26:14.630 --> 00:26:15.740
the bottom.

00:26:15.740 --> 00:26:18.480
PROFESSOR: And so all of this,
then, represents side bands.

00:26:18.480 --> 00:26:19.050
Is that--

00:26:19.050 --> 00:26:19.330
SANDY HILL: That's right.

00:26:19.330 --> 00:26:23.450
Those are the side bands due to
the square wave modulation.

00:26:23.450 --> 00:26:26.130
Going back to the simplest,
the sinusoidal carrier.

00:26:26.130 --> 00:26:30.330
Another thing we can do is to
vary the frequency of the

00:26:30.330 --> 00:26:32.790
sinusoidal signal that's
modulating it.

00:26:32.790 --> 00:26:34.890
I'll make it higher.

00:26:34.890 --> 00:26:37.650
And you'll notice that the side
bands wander away from

00:26:37.650 --> 00:26:40.230
the carrier signal
in the spectrum.

00:26:40.230 --> 00:26:43.130
The spectrum, the carrier signal
of that, doesn't have a

00:26:43.130 --> 00:26:46.040
frequency that's changing
as I do this.

00:26:46.040 --> 00:26:48.900
It's just the width of
the band, due to

00:26:48.900 --> 00:26:49.990
the modulating signal.

00:26:49.990 --> 00:26:51.350
PROFESSOR: So this
is the carrier.

00:26:51.350 --> 00:26:52.740
And these are the side bands.

00:26:52.740 --> 00:26:53.280
SANDY HILL: That's right.

00:26:53.280 --> 00:26:56.570
Now as we go out very far, those
side bands get gobbled

00:26:56.570 --> 00:26:58.215
up by the carrier itself.

00:26:58.215 --> 00:27:01.510
I'll come back to a nice
reasonable point there.

00:27:01.510 --> 00:27:09.060
PROFESSOR: OK, now, we can
change also the carrier

00:27:09.060 --> 00:27:13.790
frequency and, as Sandy's
indicated, various parameters.

00:27:13.790 --> 00:27:17.690
Now let me just point out, since
I didn't previously,

00:27:17.690 --> 00:27:21.380
that the frequency scale that
we're looking at here is a

00:27:21.380 --> 00:27:24.790
frequency scale out
to 20 kilohertz.

00:27:24.790 --> 00:27:28.770
And we had talked about--
or Sandy had indicated--

00:27:28.770 --> 00:27:33.210
that we can change the
carrier signal shape.

00:27:33.210 --> 00:27:38.550
And let me change the carrier
signal from a sine wave to a

00:27:38.550 --> 00:27:39.970
square wave.

00:27:39.970 --> 00:27:43.190
Now you haven't seen any change
on this particular

00:27:43.190 --> 00:27:47.680
display , but let me change
the frequency scale.

00:27:47.680 --> 00:27:54.060
And what you see now is the
modulating signal showing up

00:27:54.060 --> 00:27:58.090
around harmonics associated
with the carrier.

00:27:58.090 --> 00:28:03.100
And those harmonics will go
away when we go back to a

00:28:03.100 --> 00:28:04.630
sinusoidal carrier.

00:28:04.630 --> 00:28:06.300
SANDY HILL: This is actually
called a ring modulator.

00:28:06.300 --> 00:28:09.600
It's very simple to multiply
a signal by a square wave.

00:28:09.600 --> 00:28:11.220
It's just a chopping process.

00:28:11.220 --> 00:28:13.770
And so a square wave carrier
signal is very

00:28:13.770 --> 00:28:15.380
convenient to generate.

00:28:15.380 --> 00:28:19.676
And then you simply filter out
the higher order harmonics.

00:28:19.676 --> 00:28:21.660
PROFESSOR: Right, I'll
go back to the

00:28:21.660 --> 00:28:23.850
scale that we had before.

00:28:23.850 --> 00:28:28.160
And Sandy had also commented
that we can

00:28:28.160 --> 00:28:31.190
change the carrier level.

00:28:31.190 --> 00:28:33.870
And let's do that on
the modulator box.

00:28:33.870 --> 00:28:38.140
We could do that either by
changing a DC offset on the

00:28:38.140 --> 00:28:40.700
modulating signal or by changing
the amount of carrier

00:28:40.700 --> 00:28:41.950
that's injected.

00:28:41.950 --> 00:28:46.170
And as we decrease the amount
of carrier, in fact, going

00:28:46.170 --> 00:28:49.550
down to no carrier at all
or almost no carrier.

00:28:49.550 --> 00:28:51.280
That's suppressed carrier.

00:28:51.280 --> 00:28:55.340
We have only the two side bands
and the signal is now

00:28:55.340 --> 00:28:58.320
highly over-modulated.

00:28:58.320 --> 00:29:05.390
We bring the carrier back up and
when we do that, then we

00:29:05.390 --> 00:29:11.350
are reducing the percent
modulation and simultaneously

00:29:11.350 --> 00:29:15.420
obviously related to that is
changing the carrier level.

00:29:15.420 --> 00:29:21.230
Now I had indicated in previous
lectures that

00:29:21.230 --> 00:29:24.270
reducing the carrier is
efficient in terms of power

00:29:24.270 --> 00:29:30.250
transmission, but requires a
synchronous demodulator,

00:29:30.250 --> 00:29:34.730
whereas if there's carrier
injected, as we have here, so

00:29:34.730 --> 00:29:36.200
that we're not over-modulating--

00:29:36.200 --> 00:29:38.700
the percent modulation
is less than 100--

00:29:38.700 --> 00:29:42.180
then because of the shape of the
time wave form, as you can

00:29:42.180 --> 00:29:47.480
see here, you can do the
demodulation with a more or

00:29:47.480 --> 00:29:50.520
less simple envelope detector.

00:29:50.520 --> 00:29:54.500
And in fact, a envelope detector
of the type that

00:29:54.500 --> 00:29:57.720
we've talked about before is
exactly what is used in AM

00:29:57.720 --> 00:30:01.560
radios, because of the fact
that it's so inexpensive.

00:30:01.560 --> 00:30:05.650
And so here the power
transmitted required is

00:30:05.650 --> 00:30:09.800
higher, but the demodulator,
based on using an envelope

00:30:09.800 --> 00:30:12.280
detector, is considerably
simpler.

00:30:15.150 --> 00:30:18.900
Well, speaking of AM radios,
what we'd like to now

00:30:18.900 --> 00:30:24.030
demonstrate is modulation and
demodulation with an AM radio,

00:30:24.030 --> 00:30:27.710
which Sandy happens
to have here.

00:30:27.710 --> 00:30:31.670
And let's see, I guess, what
you're going to do, Sandy, is

00:30:31.670 --> 00:30:32.815
take it apart for us, right?

00:30:32.815 --> 00:30:33.070
SANDY HILL: Right.

00:30:33.070 --> 00:30:34.930
I've taken off the back.

00:30:34.930 --> 00:30:39.260
And I'm just now going to slip
out the guts of it all, and

00:30:39.260 --> 00:30:42.940
try and set it up so you can see
it conveniently, such as

00:30:42.940 --> 00:30:44.846
right there.

00:30:44.846 --> 00:30:47.140
PROFESSOR: Now, this is your
daughter's radio that you

00:30:47.140 --> 00:30:47.750
promised to give back.?

00:30:47.750 --> 00:30:50.480
SANDY HILL: I would say was
my daughter's radio.

00:30:50.480 --> 00:30:53.250
And now let's start attaching
clip leads, because what we're

00:30:53.250 --> 00:30:56.480
going to want to do is to be
able to see the signals coming

00:30:56.480 --> 00:30:57.580
out of the radio.

00:30:57.580 --> 00:31:00.890
We want to see both the audio
and then the modulated signal

00:31:00.890 --> 00:31:02.800
and try and see them on
the oscilloscope.

00:31:02.800 --> 00:31:05.005
So I'll start setting
that up now.

00:31:05.005 --> 00:31:05.700
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:31:05.700 --> 00:31:06.760
Let me--

00:31:06.760 --> 00:31:11.220
while you're doing that-- also
just comment that the kind of

00:31:11.220 --> 00:31:13.790
AM radio that we're looking
at here is called a

00:31:13.790 --> 00:31:15.350
superheterodyne receiver.

00:31:15.350 --> 00:31:19.380
And the way that it does the
demodulation is not exactly

00:31:19.380 --> 00:31:20.950
the way we've talked about
it in the lectures.

00:31:20.950 --> 00:31:22.320
It's very close.

00:31:22.320 --> 00:31:25.770
The idea is this the RF signal,
the radio frequency

00:31:25.770 --> 00:31:29.790
signal, first gets modulated
down to what's called an IF

00:31:29.790 --> 00:31:32.320
stage-- the intermediate
frequency stage.

00:31:32.320 --> 00:31:36.840
And then it's that signal that
goes to an envelope detector

00:31:36.840 --> 00:31:39.280
of the type we've talked
about to generate

00:31:39.280 --> 00:31:41.930
the demodulated signal.

00:31:41.930 --> 00:31:45.900
So, I guess what Sandy has
some probes on are the RF

00:31:45.900 --> 00:31:48.540
input and a ground--

00:31:48.540 --> 00:31:49.260
SANDY HILL: That's right.

00:31:49.260 --> 00:31:50.960
The red lead here is a ground.

00:31:50.960 --> 00:31:53.650
It's common for both the signals
we'll be looking at.

00:31:53.650 --> 00:31:54.520
This is at the audio.

00:31:54.520 --> 00:31:56.660
We're actually looking at the
signal going directly into the

00:31:56.660 --> 00:31:58.720
speaker across these
two leads.

00:31:58.720 --> 00:32:01.810
And then this probe down here,
which I found by hunting and

00:32:01.810 --> 00:32:05.740
pecking, is the IF signal, the
intermediate frequency signal,

00:32:05.740 --> 00:32:08.490
with a station on it that I'll
now try and get something that

00:32:08.490 --> 00:32:09.380
sounds reasonable.

00:32:09.380 --> 00:32:12.146
[RADIO FEEDBACK]

00:32:12.146 --> 00:32:12.610
SANDY HILL: OK.

00:32:12.610 --> 00:32:13.710
A little sports.

00:32:13.710 --> 00:32:15.755
PROFESSOR: Never quite know what
you're going to get when

00:32:15.755 --> 00:32:16.910
you turn this on.

00:32:16.910 --> 00:32:18.160
SANDY HILL: That's
right, you don't.

00:32:22.380 --> 00:32:23.960
Make some adjustments there.

00:32:23.960 --> 00:32:27.500
And what you can see right
here is the audio signal.

00:32:27.500 --> 00:32:31.480
I'll give it a little
bit more game.

00:32:31.480 --> 00:32:34.510
And this is the actual
intermediate frequency,

00:32:34.510 --> 00:32:36.380
modulated by the audio.

00:32:36.380 --> 00:32:39.010
And there's a correspondence
between them that goes by

00:32:39.010 --> 00:32:42.180
awfully fast, but I think it's
pretty simple to see.

00:32:42.180 --> 00:32:45.550
PROFESSOR: So basically the top
trace is the envelope of

00:32:45.550 --> 00:32:46.170
the bottom right.

00:32:46.170 --> 00:32:47.000
SANDY HILL: That's right.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:49.860
This is what comes out of
the envelope detector.

00:32:49.860 --> 00:32:52.800
And this is the signal into the
envelope detector, in this

00:32:52.800 --> 00:32:55.930
particular radio.

00:32:55.930 --> 00:32:59.850
What I'd like to do for a last
experiment is what we've been

00:32:59.850 --> 00:33:00.700
doing at this point--

00:33:00.700 --> 00:33:02.470
I'll turn this off
for a moment--

00:33:02.470 --> 00:33:05.190
is we're taking something that's
coming in over the

00:33:05.190 --> 00:33:08.350
airwaves, as they used to say,
and we're simply viewing it.

00:33:08.350 --> 00:33:10.690
What I'd like to do now is
generate our own radio

00:33:10.690 --> 00:33:13.390
frequency signal, tune it
up so this radio is

00:33:13.390 --> 00:33:15.160
going to hear it--

00:33:15.160 --> 00:33:16.300
whatever that means--

00:33:16.300 --> 00:33:18.710
and display it here.

00:33:18.710 --> 00:33:23.170
What we're going to do then is
use the audio oscillator,

00:33:23.170 --> 00:33:26.710
along with the amplitude
modulator.

00:33:26.710 --> 00:33:30.060
And we're going to take from the
output now the lead here.

00:33:30.060 --> 00:33:32.020
And this will act
as the antenna.

00:33:32.020 --> 00:33:34.900
This device was not designed
to put out a lot of power.

00:33:34.900 --> 00:33:37.550
But fortunately we don't have a
lot of distance to go over.

00:33:37.550 --> 00:33:40.480
What I'm going to do is turn
myself into an antenna--

00:33:40.480 --> 00:33:43.250
I'm basically 150 pounds
of salt water--

00:33:43.250 --> 00:33:46.380
and when I touch this, the
signal coming in here, which

00:33:46.380 --> 00:33:49.550
is radiating a little from the
wire, is going to suddenly

00:33:49.550 --> 00:33:52.150
radiate from my whole body and
hopefully will be enough

00:33:52.150 --> 00:33:53.450
to be picked up.

00:33:53.450 --> 00:33:58.130
So what I'll do is I'm going
to turn this on--

00:33:58.130 --> 00:33:59.800
excuse the noise.

00:33:59.800 --> 00:34:02.850
Now I've set this up so it's
tuned to a particular radio

00:34:02.850 --> 00:34:04.900
station, and I hope
I can find it now.

00:34:07.850 --> 00:34:09.100
It takes a little fussing.

00:34:14.179 --> 00:34:15.429
That's not it.

00:34:18.060 --> 00:34:19.710
That sounds like it now.

00:34:19.710 --> 00:34:22.210
OK.

00:34:22.210 --> 00:34:25.929
PROFESSOR: So this gets billed
as Sandy Hill, human antenna.

00:34:25.929 --> 00:34:27.580
SANDY HILL: That's right.

00:34:27.580 --> 00:34:30.920
What you're looking at here is
I've got the antenna at this

00:34:30.920 --> 00:34:33.630
point, and what we're going
to do is you're

00:34:33.630 --> 00:34:35.110
seeing the audio signal.

00:34:35.110 --> 00:34:37.980
This is coming from the signal
generator up here.

00:34:37.980 --> 00:34:42.699
And this is the intermediate
frequency signal again.

00:34:42.699 --> 00:34:45.389
You can hear it's much stronger
when my body becomes

00:34:45.389 --> 00:34:47.250
the antenna.

00:34:47.250 --> 00:34:48.909
And I'll leave it
on for a second.

00:34:48.909 --> 00:34:51.872
And I can switch to
square wave--

00:34:51.872 --> 00:34:54.199
doesn't look much like
a square wave.

00:34:54.199 --> 00:34:56.590
Various things.

00:34:56.590 --> 00:34:59.780
There's significant distortion,
because of all the

00:34:59.780 --> 00:35:02.290
transformations that the signal
is going through.

00:35:02.290 --> 00:35:06.870
But it does indeed work, and
we're picking up a frequency

00:35:06.870 --> 00:35:09.360
that the radio is tuned to.

00:35:09.360 --> 00:35:10.170
And that's it.

00:35:10.170 --> 00:35:13.590
PROFESSOR: So Sandy has
now been modulated and

00:35:13.590 --> 00:35:14.080
demodulated.

00:35:14.080 --> 00:35:16.280
SANDY HILL: That's right.

00:35:16.280 --> 00:35:19.090
PROFESSOR: Well, hopefully, all
the things that we've gone

00:35:19.090 --> 00:35:23.800
through in the process of this
tape and this set of

00:35:23.800 --> 00:35:27.250
demonstrations gives you a feel
for at least some of the

00:35:27.250 --> 00:35:30.920
things that we've talked about
so far in the course.

00:35:30.920 --> 00:35:35.430
And Sandy, I'd really like to
thank you for joining us, for

00:35:35.430 --> 00:35:38.260
sharing your insights with us,
as well as sharing your

00:35:38.260 --> 00:35:38.940
equipment with us.

00:35:38.940 --> 00:35:39.300
Thanks a lot.

00:35:39.300 --> 00:35:40.210
SANDY HILL: It was a treat.

00:35:40.210 --> 00:35:41.460
Thank you.

